{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a8932c42-f667-4e7f-9801-7758bc2dedce","content":"In .NET MAUI, use the **lifecycle events** API in your `MauiProgram.cs` (or anywhere you configure the app builder):\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity => { /* your code */ })\n        .OnStop(activity => { /* your code */ }));\n#endif\n\n#if IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* your code */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;` (and platform-specific usings).\n- Use `#if` preprocessor directives to keep platform code from compiling on other targets.\n- Other events are available too (e.g., `OnResume`, `WillEnterForeground`, `OnCreate`, etc.).\n- This approach avoids subclassing platform `Activity`/`AppDelegate` for simple scenarios.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0dc7ef7c-3874-46af-86cc-31965bf8f8cf","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI - specifically Android's OnPause/OnStop and iOS's DidEnterBackground. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI that I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.","outputTokens":334,"requestId":"E850:29C906:25C5CB4:29D1532:69F93EF9"},"id":"b72e9b1e-d75e-43bf-bf09-a96a8b4611a9","timestamp":"2026-05-05T00:51:13.866Z","parentId":"a1fcee7a-e2ad-4cbd-9aec-998cc7bce7c7"}
